**MAC MINI AGENT SERVER**

**ADR-034 — Hardware Telemetry Collector**

**Status: DECIDED**

Date: March 29, 2026

Phase: 1.5  |  Deploys ~2 weeks post-setup-day

Owner: Sheldon Wheeler

**NIST Coverage:  AC · AU · SI**

Tooling: mac-stats.com (Stats by exelban) · hw_collector.py · PostgreSQL hardware_metrics table

# 1.  Context and Decision

ADR-033 (Operator Dashboard Metrics Framework) identified hardware-layer metrics—thermals, CPU P/E-core utilization, GPU utilization, ANE power draw, memory pressure, fan speed, and system power draw—as Phase 1 requirements sourced from “iStat Menus / iStatistica Pro.” During Session 9 planning the operator elected to replace that commercial dependency with two free alternatives:

•  mac-stats.com (Stats by exelban) — open-source MIT-licensed menu bar monitor for live ambient display. Free. No persistent storage. Covers the same menu bar instrument panel role as iStat Menus at zero cost.

•  hw_collector.py — a purpose-built Python scraper (this ADR) that polls powermetrics at 60-second intervals and writes to a new hardware_metrics PostgreSQL table. Provides the persistent history, session recording, and presentation-quality data that MacPulse would have supplied commercially.

The motivation follows the same principle applied to NemoClaw: borrow the concept, own the implementation. The result is a hardware telemetry layer that is fully integrated with the existing PostgreSQL audit infrastructure, inherits all existing backup and retention policies, and is queryable by the same SQL tooling already in use for agent_actions.

Decision: Adopt hw_collector.py as the hardware telemetry data source for ADR-033 dashboard metrics. Deploy Stats (mac-stats.com) for live menu bar display. Retire MacPulse from the recommended tooling list. Add hardware_metrics as a Phase 1.5 PostgreSQL table under the same dev account and retention schedule as agent_actions.

